Perl 5.6.1 on Red Hat Linux:
(For perl modules, see file build-perl-module)

Per directions in INSTALL:
	rm -f config.sh Policy.sh
	sh Configure -de
	make
	make test
	su
	make install
	cd pod
	make all html

Perl 5.6.1 does not contain an Info version of the manual; however, I
found a version at ftp://ftp.cpan.org/pub/CPAN/doc/manual/texinfo/.
Download from ftp://ftp.cpan.org/pub/CPAN/doc/manual/texinfo/perl5/.
  tar zxvf perl-5.6-info.tar.gz
  cd perl-5.6-info/info
  rm *unsplit*
  su
  cp -pf * /usr/local/info

At "make test", I got:
  op/lfs...............FAILED at test 6
so I ran
  cd t
  ./perl harness 
which gave me:
  Failed Test Status Wstat Total Fail  Failed  List of Failed
  -----------------------------------------------------------
  op/lfs.t                    17    4  23.53%  6, 8, 10, 12
then I ran
  ./perl op/lfs.t
This indicated that the problem is with support for large files; maybe
I just don't have enough free disk space at the moment.

===========================================================================

UW:
 * create a build directory under /tmp or /usr/tmp
 * symlink from there to /uns/src/perl5.004-building and the .tar.gz file
 * ./perl5.004-building test
   This produced
	op/stat...........FAILED on test 4
   but then "cd ./t; ./perl op/stat.t" produced
	not ok 4
	#4 If test op/stat.t fails test 4, check if you are on a tmpfs
	#4 of some sort.  Building in /tmp sometimes has this problem.
	#4	:866760644: != :866760644:
   so I relaxed
 * ./perl5.004-building install
 * ./perl5.004-building h2ph
 * chmod -R g+w /uns/share/lib/perl5.004
 * chmod -R g+w /uns/lib/perl5.004
 * copy libraries from 5.003 site-perl directory to 5.004 site-perl
 * install 5.004 Info manual

Everything worked on Solaris, old Linux; but on new Linux, I got:
  Checking your choice of C compiler, libs, and flags for coherency...
  I've tried to compile and run a simple program with:
	  gcc -O -Dbool=char -DHAS_BOOL -I/usr/local/include -L/usr/local/lib -o try try.c -lgdbm -ldb -ldl -lm -lc
	  ./try
  and I got the following output:
    /usr/i486-linux/bin/ld: cannot open -ldl: No such file or directory
  I can't compile the test program.
  (The supplied flags might be incorrect with this C compiler.)
  You have a BIG problem.  Shall I abort Configure [y]  
though libdl.so.1 is in /lib, which is in my LD_LIBRARY_PATH.
It's right to build on old Linux, because then things work for both; if I
build only on new Linux, then old Linux boxes can't run it.

